Here's how to implement this in .NET MAUI Shell:

## 1. Override `OnBackButtonPressed` + Custom Toolbar Item

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public EditProductPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
        {
            TextOverride = "Cancel",
            Command = new Command(async () => await ConfirmAndNavigateBack())
        });
    }

    // Handles hardware/OS back button (Android, etc.)
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Can't await here, so fire-and-forget
        MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () =>
            await ConfirmAndNavigateBack());

        return true; // Cancel default navigation
    }

    private async Task ConfirmAndNavigateBack()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            await Shell.Current.GoBack();
            return;
        }

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
            await Shell.Current.GoBack();
    }
}
```

## Key points

| Concern | Mechanism |
|---------|-----------|
| Custom back button text | `Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior` with `TextOverride` |
| Intercept software back | `BackButtonBehavior.Command` |
| Intercept hardware back (Android) | Override `OnBackButtonPressed()`, return `true` to cancel |
| Cancel navigation | Simply don't call `GoBack()` |

## 2. Track unsaved changes

Set `_hasUnsavedChanges = true` whenever a form field changes (e.g., bind to `TextChanged` events or use a dirty-tracking mechanism in your ViewModel).

> **Note:** Shell doesn't have a built-in "navigation guard" like web routers. The pattern above—intercepting both the hardware back button and the Shell back button behavior—is the standard approach.
